Title: The Fall of Wisconsin: The Conservative Conquest of a Progressive Bastion and the Future of American Politics
Author: Dan  Kaufman
My Review:
Perhaps my favorite book of the year. Do not read before bedtime or thoughts of Fitzgerald and Walker will keep you up. Don’t read the rest of this review if you’re uninterested in some of my political thoughts.

This book made it clear how uninformed I am of Wisconsin’s history (including its recent history). There a lots of things to be proud of in Wisconsin’s past: progressivism, protection of workers’ rights, and a commitment to environmental decency.

This book also supports a recent revelation (recent to me): politicians like Walker and Trump are not so much a disease, but instead symptoms of a system that seems to be fundamentally broken. Walker’s ideas were neither new nor original, but that doesn’t change how destructive they have been. It might make you feel a little better to know the state wasn’t duped by his own Ideas, or it might make you feel worse to have a better understanding on how much influence outside groups and money had on the state.

This book did not make me more hopeful.
